<subSubSection box="[264,428,684,707]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="15.[264,428,684,707]" box="[264,428,684,707]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<taxonomicName box="[264,428,684,707]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">REDUVIIDAE</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[264,1323,759,985]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
Because of their roles as vectors of 
<emphasis box="[677,910,759,784]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<taxonomicName box="[677,905,759,784]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Trypanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="cruzi">Trypanosoma cruzi</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
the causative agent of Chagas’ disease, species in the subfamily 
<taxonomicName box="[628,770,799,825]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Triatominae">Triatominae</taxonomicName>
are the most medically important Heteroptera in the New World. 
<taxonomicName box="[520,662,839,865]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Triatominae">Triatominae</taxonomicName>
are occasionally found infected with arboviruses and plague bacilli (Garcia 
<emphasis box="[528,587,879,904]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[595,657,879,905]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" value="2000.0">2000</number>
, Ames 
<emphasis box="[746,805,879,904]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[813,872,879,905]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" value="1954.0">1954</number>
)) but they are only known to transmit 
<taxonomicName box="[264,352,919,944]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Trypanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="cruzi">
<emphasis box="[264,352,919,944]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">T. cruzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Tejera" authorityName="Tejera" box="[409,741,919,945]" class="Kinetoplastea" family="Trypanosomatidae" genus="Trypanosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Trypanosomatida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="rangeli">
<emphasis box="[409,661,919,944]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Trypanosoma rangeli</emphasis>
Tejera
</taxonomicName>
to humans. 
<taxonomicName box="[892,1034,919,945]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Triatominae">Triatominae</taxonomicName>
are vectors of hemogregarines to lizards (Smith 
<number box="[559,622,959,985]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" value="1996.0">1996</number>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
